oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Louis Anfenger Europe Trip Journal
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Anfenger, Louis,--1842-1900
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Diary kept by Louis Anfenger, who was a Denver businessman and Colorado State legislator, as well as a founder of Congregation Emanuel, B'nai B'rith and the National Jewish Hospital for Consumptives. This journal documents Louise and Louis Anfenger's trip to Europe in 1890. The tan leather pocket inside the back cover holds a German calling card for Witz Deszo. Entries are short and factual, for example, the first entry states: "Saturday June 28, 1890. Left New York at 2 o'clock pm on steamer Elbe. Man fell overboard and was drowned. Weather pleasant." Other entries include monetary spending, locales and weather related matters.

oai_dc:dc.dc:description: A dark purple velvet bound prayer book in German and Hebrew, published in Germany, 1878. (Hebrew is read from right to left.) There are no markings on the spine; the clasp is metal and has elaborate scrolling.

oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Wedding Gown with Waist Drape
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: Clothing and dress
Weddings
Peterman, Joseph,--1898-1962
Peterman, Sophie Miller,--1900-1986
Women's clothing
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: A wedding gown with a waist drape. The bodice has three layers: bottom layer consists of ornate copper threads on ivory satin fabric (originally part of another garment made approximately ten years earlier); the middle layer is silk, and the top layer is silk jacquard. From the waist down, there are two layers: bottom layer is a fine thin silk underlay and the top layer is an off-white silk jacquard overdress. There are capped chiffon sleeves and a cotton petersham waistband that also serves to attach much of the gathering of the waist drape. The dress has an added drape (additional panel of fabric) that begins at the gathered waist on the left side and wraps around the back of the dress and ends over the right front leg in a series of attached drapes. A separate piece of silk jacquard, lined in off-white silk with one end angularly cut, has a silk ribbon attached on the lined side. The angular edge of the separate piece of silk would hang over the shoulder and the remainder would drape over the back. Originally belonged to Sophie Miller Peterman.
Title supplied by archivist.
